76561198003991636,Not Recommended,227860,12742652,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,The AdmiraL,"Revised Review:It's been a long almost 3 years since that last review and there was very very little hope in sight. Credit to the developers; they have stuck through the pain and the vitrol and delivered a game that while fun; is also flawed. I've done my best to give a balanced look; as while i can certainly say it is a far better game than when I posted this review in '14; I can also be biased as I have put money against a product that for some time looked like a waste of money.For those wanting a high level view of why there are so many negative reviews; Castle Story initially released on kickstarter; then 2 years of pure re-factoring the game built up a negative image and a burnt community. They've attempted to 'rebuilt' the community as such; but the damage had been done. The name was tarnished but to their credit, they've stuck through it and delivered a game that is fun, but ultimately flawed.The positives is that this is a light hearted castle defense game. It's core 'feature' that draws most people in is the 'invasion' mode. This is something that players have been screaming for ever since Stronghold 1 / Stronghold Crusader. The essense of building your castle and defending it is something that is almost engrained in our blood.Wave after wave of corruptrons to come and destroy your designs and castles. As the game has progressed from '14 to '17; additional monsters were added. Minitrons, a big one that tosses the minitrons, and finally a warlock. While 4 enemy types does sound appealing, there is still that distinct lack of utility with the invaders. Many of them do not force you to change your playstyle, or plan proactively. Adding features (should they continue to) such as wall climbing corruptron or a huge corruptron that throws massive rocks at your walls would most certainly add to the game. The issue moving forward for the developers is to create additional enemies that create that 'siege-like' enemies while sticking with the theme. Still, simply adding these 2x enemies I believe would greatly improve the game.At the same time, while clunky, you are most certainly able to design grand castles and strongholds. The developers have spent a lot of time on the pathfinding and it does show; the AI while still buggy is quite proficient. There are issues with the AI; most certainly the main one is the seeming ability for bricktrons to drop everything they carry and watch all your resources scatter to the four winds - a huge negative in my books.Besides adding enemies and improved pathfinding, the developers have also added in several classes, minor crafting, gems, tunnels, blocks and architectural features. While the list is quite small, the above has most certainly assisted in shifting this game from more of a 'light' hearted castle to defense to something with a bit more 'meat.'The multiplayer is a component I will not review on. I bought this game purely for the single player and I'm more than happy to let others who have experienced multiplayer comment on this.The negative is that the game is still clunky. The UI is poor, blueprints can be a pain and at times the bricktrons break. The game is costed $20, which may also seem quite a high price for what feels like a clunky game. There is a lack of balance in the game, you will find yourself starved of previous resources. The lack of variety in corruptrons can get quite boring, where you are facing the same enemies over and over again. The addition of further enemy types would certainly improve the experience, one that tends to fall flat at times. There is also a lack of content; there is no feeling of being 'overwhelmed' that stronghold offers you when you face gigantic armies and you hide behind your walls.The difficulty is yet to be fully realised and balanced, and many players are caught out by the early invasion timers. The inability to generate additional resources and you eventually starve out of resources is also a problem that hurts the longevity of the game, but by that time you are probably tired of your castle and the same old enemies attacking.Castle Story is a game that still holds terrific potential. Besides the flaws in it's grand design, poor balancing and lack of content, it is only a few addtional features and content away from turning from a fun but average game to something that is a superior product. For Castle Story to fully realise it's potential, it needs further content before the paint of polish.I must add that I do not know the developers. I do not know what their future plans for Castle Story hold. But if this is the game you were hoping for as the second coming of a light version of Stronghold, for now, you will need to seek elsewhere.-----Previous Review: Posted: 2 Nov, 2014 @ 11:14pmNo progress whatsoever.Until that changes, DO NOT BUY THIS GAME."
