76561198091467820,Not Recommended,227860,30519276,Posted: 14 March,all,Solumn Trade,"I DO like this game. But there are some issues. The biggest, glaring issue, is that castles are simply are NOT the meta in this game. The second is that, despite being a micromanagement simulator, micro in combat does not fly well, although it's absolutely necessary. The first thing I'd like to advise is, save often, and if you lose ANYONE in the hoard mode, you need to reload the save.Now, about the castles part. They simply ARE NOT the most effective defense. You are building castles against creatures that have the ability to punch through walls, and eat several arrows, essentially anti-castle creatures. You don't even have all the historical options to build the castle with anyway. You will simply lack the ability to create arrow slits, machicolations (although I suppose you can make one with the beams and beam slot block, I don't think the archers can use them), and proper gate houses with murder holes. Even if all these things were possible, the micro required to manage these things just isn't there.I've tried several occasions to build a proper keep, three bricks thick. I got to four or five bricks tall before they started completely overwhelming the defense, drilling a hole into the wall, and using that hole as cover. At a certain point, the repair and reset time eats up all your gathering time, meaning the castle will never be completed before you've lost. Now, it seems that, if you leave the castle without a door, you can minimize the damage to the castle, but then your Bricktrons are vulnerable, and at the mercy of you managing their own stupidity.If you want to get to high rounds, it seems the proper way to go about things is to create mazes, full of hurdles that will slow the Corruptrons down. You want to give the Corruptrons a seemingly easy path to your crystal, so that they aren't compelled to break any walls. It takes them extra time to climb up and jump down from blocks. Then, you want to line up your archers so that they face down a long corridor of hurdles, and have your knights hiding around a corner at the end. But getting to high rounds isn't necessarily what I bought the game for, it was more or less for building castles while doing it. Which isn't the most efficient way to accomplish getting higher rounds. That's a problem, in my opinion.Now, about it being a micromanagement simulator. Many people have had problems with the Bricktron building AI, but I've overcome it simply by realizing the sort of order they do things. You cannot create an entire castle in blueprints, and simply let them go about it. It's all about LAYERS. In order to make sure they build things in proper order, you must only place the bricks that immediately come next. So I'm okay with the building AI, more or less.But then comes the combat AI...it's frustrating. Perhaps the tools exist that are a better option than trying to click on a weak Knight and spam-clicking so that they will retreat, or clicking on a tiny point in the command bar (which doen't show which unit is injured), but I haven't found it. There are commands to make the Knights stand still, but they WON'T. Almost every time you try to force them back to the crystal for healing, they immediately want to run back and die (that is, if you tried to build a keep around your crystal like me. If there's enough distance that the AI will not detect the enemy, i.e. the end of a maze build, they won't be as stupid). When in a cluster, it's hard to select the Knight you need to fall back, and it's really annoying that sometimes they won't give you time to select other wounded Knights to fall back before they suicidally try to jump back into the fray and get themselves killed, not to meantion blocking other troops that need to fall back. As for Archers, they have trouble aiming downward.If I were to make suggestions, I would like to ask Sauropod studios to take a look at other RTS games, as well as do more research on actual castles, and make improvements based upon that. A good way to improve the AI is to give the option for a proper stance system, that doesn't reset every time you are trying to move them. Also, clicking in empty space should deselect all things, rather than having to click on the task to unselect. Remove the number keys from the task list, they aren't used and are better suited for creating groups.It is possible to soldier through these faults, but many quality-of-life changes are needed."
