76561198030783476,Recommended,227860,35130149,Posted: 22 September,all,cmfic,"This is an enjoyable RTS game, as far as it goes. It includes some relatively unique mechanics and can be a lot of fun. Unfortunately, there are some major drawbacks, which, hopefully, the developers will remedy soon:1. Overwhelming micromanagement. At present, you cannot do anything but look around the map while in pause mode. This means that if you have more than a handful of ""bricktrons,"" they can be impossible to control in a timely manner, much like herding cats, especially consdering #2.2. Lag. As the number of units and structures in the game increase the lag gets extremely frustrating as it can take several seconds (up to about 15-20) for your units to respond to a direct order. The developers seem to have based this game on the brictrons having a modicum of intelligence in that they can determine, on their own, the priority of the next task on the todo list (subject to any priorities you assign in the UI). The cost of this is that it takes time for the bricktrons to deduce this priority and, depending on the map and mode (Sandbox, Invasion, or Conquest), can literally make or break your game.  BTW, Invasion mode is, unwinnable, like any castle defense game. The best you can hope for is surviving multiple waves of bad guys (""Corruptrons"").3. Need for Optimization: Some might say the lag problem is the fault of old or less powerful equipment. While this may have some truth to it, the game needs to be tweaked and optimized. It's a bit of a stretch to expect people to go out and drop a couple of $K to be able to play a $25 game. (I say this as strictly a PC player. I do not own nor do I play consoles, so I have no idea what problems or costs might be related to those game systems.)Having said all of this, I still would recommend this game. It's fun (to a point) and is reasonably priced in today's market.  I have only played the game for 5 hours or so, at the time of this review but so far the entertainment value has been about $5/hour, or about equal to seeing a movie. But the longer I play the game, the cost of entertainment decreases, unlike seeing a movie multiple times.What remains to be seen is where the devs will take this promising game as it matures.  IMHO.UPDATED 9/24/2017: After several more hours of game time, I want to add a few more items to my list of fixes needed.4. Pathfinding: As the game progresses and you have about a dozen bricktrons, you'll find that they easily get lost and sometimes wander off into enemy territory. One thing to watch for is if their path is blocked by fallen bricks, etc., but beyond that pathfinding degrades quickly at about 12 bricktrons.  Coupled with lag as your structures increase, late game activities involve a lot of work if you are to survive.5. AI: The AI seems to either go to sleep or is unable to handle complex situations. For example, say you build a wall that's 2 rows deep. If the outer layer gets damaged to the point where you need to replace bricks (not covered by a repair task), the AI doesn't seem to understand that you are patching a hole and the hole in the outer layer persists.Still giving this a thumbs up in hopes the devs will fix these problems."
