76561198030780576,Recommended,227860,24254249,"Posted: 11 July, 2016",all,Nik,"Let me start by briefly describing what castle story is. The game is a voxel based, real-time strategy tower defense hybrid with a world editor and a building system that allows for a lot of creativity with a good physics engine. It brings back memories of my childhood playing with Legos (without the mess), allows for builds similar to Minecraft (using blueprints, gathered resources and workers instead of having to do everything through first person) and includes tower defense style elements in a world of floating islands in the sky.The most popular game mode is called Invasion and it tests your defenses against waves of an ever-increasing amount of enemies that can knock your archers off walls, break down your defenses and even throw enemies into your base! To defend yourself you have beefy knights, archers and catapults along with various floor traps such as bear traps and explosive barrels. You can alter the world to change the direction which the enemies take or create bottlenecks where you can do a lot of damage to them. You can team up with friends to help deal with more difficult maps in coop mode. There is also a game mode called conquest where you fight the corruptrons (AI) or other players (multiplayer) for control over different areas of the map with the objective of taking over the entire map. This game type makes defenses less static and brings offensive elements to the game and you can team up with your buddies to take on the AI where you each have your own bases and units. You will inevitably build defenses and leapfrog forward, capturing more and more terrain.Based on the recent improvements to the game, it seems the development team has grown, as can be seen in the increase to both the game quality and responsiveness in community feedback. The game’s most recent patch, 0.7, brought with it a lot of great changes and many people who played it before this patch and didn’t like it or had performance issues may want to try it again. There is now a world editor which is both powerful and quick and easy to use. Multiplayer has been implemented as well. Moreover, the performance of this game has improved greatly and your builders and warriors respond much better and quicker. While I did enjoy the game before the most recent patch, the game has improved leaps and bounds and it seems the developers have doubled down in their efforts to flesh it out and polish it. There is an active and growing community of mapmakers and active players as well, both new and old.However, that said there are a few cons to the game in its current form: the game still has its fair share of bugs, especially prevalent in the recently introduced multiplayer. Additionally, multiplayer can be tricky to set up, though they are working on implementing a better system/ dedicated server. The game isn’t for everyone as it demands patience and planning but can be extremely rewarding once you understand the basics. While the game might initially seem simple, there is a surprising depth to it once you get to know the mechanics and since the game is still in development, your ideas and concepts might be implemented into future patches. Looking back at how much I have played and enjoyed this game, I think it’s worth the full price, though I did buy it when it was on sale. If you are dedicated to the concept or want to support an indie developer that has doubled down its efforts, I suggest you pick it up or at least put it on your wish list and wait for it to be on sale.The verdict:If you:enjoy voxel based games that allow you to build whatever and however you want with a world editor and physics-based construction,like tower defense games that test your patience and strategic thinking in which you can immerse yourself and relax,like real-time strategy, resource management and building bases brick by brick,then this game is for you."
