76561198040164536,Not Recommended,227860,9803298,"Posted: 12 April, 2014",all,Naco,Hard to understand and control. Nothing to help a new player...
,Not Recommended,227860,34448773,Posted: 23 August,all,Sir Ventricle,"I've been playing this game on and off - pretty much after each patch - since it was in very early access, and coming back to it after full release I have to say that a lot of is much better than it used to be. I've been rooting for these guys for years now, and although development has been patchy I really want them to deliver a good game. Unfortunately, what I've seen in 7ish hours of play, mostly on survival, hasn't quite convinced me that they've succeeded in that.The good:- Love the aesthetic and general idea. I'm a massive Stronghold fan and this is basically the basics of that plus the creative elements of Minecraft. The tech tree is tiny but at least there's something of a tiered upgrade system that rewards planning and efficient placement of storage and crafting stations.- I like the task-based building/crafting/repairing idea, and how it's integrated in the UI. You hold RMB to bring up the contextual menu, then choose what task you want to set. Then you can assign units to it, allowing you to keep a prioritised list of tasks to complete.- Sandbox mode works well, particularly because the building mechanics are relatively intuitive and construction takes place quite intelligently (at least compared to early access). It's fun to build a large castle and the materials provided make it easy to build something that looks good, too.The neutral:- I haven't run into any crashes yet, unlike in the early access versions.What needs to be improved:- There NEEDS to be a tutorial. Right now, it's very difficult to tell what something does except by experimenting with it, and - combined with the complete lack of tooltips - this makes it much more difficult to appreciate the little depth there is. This leads to my next point:- There's no real depth to the game yet. As I mentioned before, the tech tree is tiny and you can in fact skip most of it (you don't need to have archers or halberdiers, you can go straight to crossbowmen and knights). In sandbox mode, where no threats apart from buggy pathfinding exist, this is fine - after all, you spend most of your time building and tech isn't a worry because you're not defending yourself. Invasion, however, becomes incredibly hard, because your units don't scale with the ever-harder-hitting waves. There's an achievement for wave 60, but since your first-tier units become obsolete by wave 10, most of your defenses after that point rely on good planning and clever layouts; this means you need to radically change strategies (from teching up to planning castle layout) and you aren't really given much time to do so. In other words: for a 1.0 release it feels like it's missing quite a bit of core content.- The difficulty curve on invasion is absolutely punishing. Related to the first point, because the difficulty derives partly from the lack of synergy between increasing invasion threat and the lack of higher-tier units, but exacerbated by some questionable design choices. Although it's possible to turn your military units back into workers, I didn't manage to find out how to do this on my own, and it offers little tactical advantage apart from upgrading units. Because it's unclear precisely how you acquire new workers (I think you can still mine for crystals, but I don't really see them), I found myself almost always undermanned either on the soldier front (because my other units were gathering resources and building defences) or on the worker front (because I needed my soldiers to defend).- All of this is made much, much worse by the AI. The pathfinding is a lot better than it used to be, and construction is done pretty well now, but nearly everything else is an exercise in frustration. Micromanagement is almost impossible, partially because selecting units is difficult in the first place (and drag-selecting them tends to select objects instead), but also because your options for unit behaviour are terrible. There are two stances: defensive, which roots the unit to the exact spot it stands on, and aggressive, which lets the unit walk over to nearby enemies. I ended up mostly using the former, since the latter means your units walk through doors (sometimes opening the castle gate to a swarm of enemies) and getting themselves killed. You can manually select targets too (though there's no way of automatically prioritising particular targets, like bigger monsters first), but good luck actually landing the right-click on especially the smaller monsters. The chief culprit here of course is the UI, but it feels like the bulk of the problem could be resolved by making unit AI more intelligent. Also, while units can stand on adjacent voxels, mass-moving a group always spaces them out by a couple of voxels, often ruining formations. Worker AI is unhelpful as well: with some exceptions they tend to just do their own thing, which can be somewhat adjusted by setting priorities, but not always. It's not often clear why a worker isn't carrying out its task, and sometimes they will automatically deselect themselves from being assigned to a task (frustratingly, for example, to the catapult - they keep wandering off while an invasion is on). This makes it very hard to plan properly because you can't really rely on any of your units to do the right thing.TL;DR:Castle Story has a unique aesthetic and has the potential to draw you into a niche that isn't really filled by anything right now. Unfortunately, a lack of polish and some significant UI and AI problems make its main game mode tedious and frustrating, and the overall product feels like it wasn't quite ready to come out of early access yet. Hopefully future updates will add more content and improve unit AI, and then we might be looking at a really interesting game."
