76561198035350466,Not Recommended,227860,14327615,"Posted: 4 February, 2015",all,jcollier,"I love the graphics and the concept, but the user interface is too complicated.  Too many m enus and too many buttons to push.  A few suggestions that might make the game easier to play...maybe some of them are already into the game, but I couldnt get far enough to find them.  I only played for about 5 hours but couldnt seem to make much progress.1) Pressing space bar everytime you want to move the camera is a pain.  Scrolling could be accomplished more easily by moving the mouse cursor to the edges of the screen.  Camera rotation should be as simple as pressing the right mouse button and moving the mouse.2) Too many menu options make it difficult to wrap ones head around the game.  For example, there are two build options. Each build option has its own menus.  Why not put them all under the same menu, and order them from simple to more complex.  Its the same with mining.    There is mining for the ground, and then a mining menu for mining cliffs.  It would be easier to put them all under the same menu.3) Creating tasks can be really fun, but not for simple things like harvesting wood.  In order to harvest wood, you have to create a wood harvesting zone and then send workers to harvest the wood.  The zone is currently too small and harvests only a few trees.  What would be really neat would be to left click on a worker, hold down the left mouse button to bring up the worker menu, then mouse button up to select the ""harvest wood"" option.  The menu dissappears and the cursor changes to an axe.  Left mouse button down where you want the center of the zone and then mouse button up when the zone is large enough (basically create a custom size circle by dragging the mouse).  You can do something similar with mining, although you could have a couple of different shapes (circle, square, straight line, etc)4)  The AI is messed up.  I dont have any suggestions there because I cant see the code, however, the little buggers keep pausing while doing tasks, If I had to guess I would say that they are stuck in a code loop.These are just a few suggestions.  I wrote code to pay for my college degree, and have been designing software for over 25 years.  One thing i learned is that the interface is everything.   This is a REALLY COOL game but its just too difficult to play."
